<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911106-0128</DOCNO><DOCID>911106-0128.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Immoral Strategies   Aimed at Third World</HL><DATE>11/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19</SO><CO>   FORGN RN</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   On Oct. 4, you reported on a $4.9 billion offering fromRJR Nabisco and cited the company's need &quot;to move swiftly&quot;into international tobacco markets in Asia, the Mideast,Eastern Europe and Mexico.   Tobacco use contributes to cancer of the mouth, upper andlower airways (including lung), esophagus, kidney, pancreas,urinary bladder and uterine cervix. It contributes to chronicnon-cancer disorders of the lung and bronchial tree as wellas coronary artery disease. One-third of the half-millioncancer deaths we shall see in the U.S. in 1991 are directlyrelated to tobacco use, generally cigarette smoking.</LP><TEXT>   As the American market for tobacco diminishes, all tobaccocompanies have developed immoral strategies to promote thisnoxious addiction to vulnerable emerging Third Worldpopulations.   The medical and scientific community asks the Americaninvestor not to support the further encroachment of tobaccoaddiction into any community. We could start by rejecting theRJR Nabisco offering.   Arthur H. Rossof, M.D.   Medical Director   MacNeal Cancer Center   Loyolay University   Stritch School of Medicine   Berwyn, Ill.</TEXT></DOC>